{"title":"Policy Filtration for RLHF to Mitigate Noise in Reward Models","domain":"RL","seeds":[{"problem":"In RLHF for LLMs, reward models trained from human preferences are often inaccurate—especially in the mid-reward region—leading PPO to learn from noisy signals and over-optimize spurious reward.", "method":"Propose Policy Filtration for PPO (PF-PPO): for each prompt, sample N responses from the current policy, rank them with the reward model, and sample a training response according to a rank-based weight vector that emphasizes more reliable regions (e.g., Best-Random, Best-Worst) while de-emphasizing mid-range rewards. Train PPO to optimize a filtered policy µθ but, in practice, use samples collected from the unfiltered policy πθ as if from µθ, changing only the sampling stage. This increases the reward–score reliability (higher R^2) and improves downstream performance, achieving SOTA among 7B models on HumanEval/MBPP and large gains on the challenging LeetCode Contest."},{"problem":"Selecting an effective filtration strategy is hard to tune via full PPO runs; a lightweight predictor is needed to decide which ranks/weights yield reliable rewards before expensive training.", "method":"Use the coefficient of determination (R^2) between reward-model outputs and actual correctness on samples generated by candidate filtered policies (using the SFT or intermediate policies) as a proxy for reward reliability. Compute R^2 by grouping similar-reward samples and fitting a linear predictor; choose strategies that maximize R^2. Empirically, R^2 correlates well with final pass@1 and favors BR/BW over BoN across training stages, guiding strategy selection prior to PPO."},{"problem":"Beyond rank-only selection, practitioners may need flexible filtration mechanisms that still avoid unreliable mid-reward samples while being robust across tasks and reward models.", "method":"Introduce alternative filtering schemes within PF-PPO: threshold-based selection (PPO-top, PPO-top-random, PPO-top-bottom) and reward reweighting (PPO-pow-k with sample weights proportional to |Rϕ|^k). Experiments show most filtering variants outperform vanilla PPO/PPO-M, with rank-based PF-PPO (BR/BW) generally strongest; R^2 remains a useful selector across these variants."}]}
